WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:12.760
So I think it's time to settle the case of R versus Python. I won't settle it, it will

00:00:12.760 --> 00:00:20.320
be settled by the Belgian Justice Department. So let the battle begin. The Belgian Justice

00:00:20.320 --> 00:00:27.879
Department had an urgent need for a traffic fine monitoring system. And both R and Python

00:00:27.879 --> 00:00:36.680
were actually on the table. Who am I? I'm Thomas Mitchum, a data science lead at AXI.

00:00:36.680 --> 00:00:43.240
AXI is an IT software and full service posit partner in Belgium and in the Netherlands.

00:00:43.240 --> 00:00:48.320
Here we're also known for the donuts at our booth. We actually settled another battle

00:00:48.320 --> 00:00:53.480
there, the battle of Dunkin' Donuts versus Stan Donuts. I'm happy to announce that Stan

00:00:53.480 --> 00:01:01.439
Donuts won today. My background is I started as an analyst, then turned architect, then

00:01:01.439 --> 00:01:10.120
turned data scientist. I learned Python from my fellow developers, and I learned R from

00:01:10.120 --> 00:01:17.000
business experts. So a little bit different. And last year, our company also gave a battle

00:01:17.040 --> 00:01:24.000
presentation. It was then Shiny versus Power BI. But so this year, R versus Python.

00:01:24.000 --> 00:01:29.320
So AXI as an IT software company is actually also responsible of building the traffic fine

00:01:29.320 --> 00:01:36.040
processing system in Belgium. So the traffic fine processing system, it's a complex system

00:01:36.040 --> 00:01:42.639
with many actors involved. The easy flow is just the police departments send fines to

00:01:42.639 --> 00:01:47.160
the fine processing system, who then send the file to the postal service, who prints

00:01:47.160 --> 00:01:51.959
these fines, deliver them to civilians, who then make payments that are matched again

00:01:51.959 --> 00:01:57.440
by the fine processing system. Each time I get a traffic fine in the mail, I get to thank

00:01:57.440 --> 00:02:04.120
the company I work for. But for the case, we'll have a look at the

00:02:04.120 --> 00:02:09.199
judge, so what the Belgian Justice Department does. We'll have a look at the suspect who

00:02:09.199 --> 00:02:14.800
has a say in R versus Python. There's two important investigations, who can deliver

00:02:14.800 --> 00:02:21.160
the quickest, and also who is the best fit for production. And like in any case, we'll

00:02:21.160 --> 00:02:26.360
have a see if we can make any kind of mediation, if a settlement is possible, and then we'll

00:02:26.360 --> 00:02:30.880
come to the verdict. So the Belgian Justice Department, so they

00:02:30.880 --> 00:02:36.619
are among many things responsible of overseeing the traffic fines. It's actually quite a large

00:02:36.619 --> 00:02:41.899
scale operation, so the collection from traffic fines in Belgium alone exceeds 500 million

00:02:41.899 --> 00:02:47.660
dollars annually. So it's actually quite a large number, so making mistakes can cost

00:02:47.660 --> 00:02:52.419
them a lot of money. But it's also a very reputational thing, where civilians really

00:02:52.419 --> 00:02:57.300
don't like to get fines, and they even like it less if they get a fine twice, if they

00:02:57.300 --> 00:03:04.500
pay it twice. So it's a process that needs to be looked at. And there were some issues

00:03:04.500 --> 00:03:10.380
with the process, and the Justice Department needed a monitoring tool to actually help

00:03:10.380 --> 00:03:17.139
smoothen that process. And then R and Python came to the table. So

00:03:17.139 --> 00:03:21.740
there's languages that can be used not only for machine learning, but also in a broader

00:03:21.740 --> 00:03:28.979
context. But of course, people are already a bit biased if they hear both languages,

00:03:28.979 --> 00:03:34.300
R and Python. Some people, if they think of R, they see it as a specifically statistical

00:03:34.300 --> 00:03:40.699
language. So it's sometimes seen as good for trivia questions like, how many people do

00:03:40.699 --> 00:03:46.820
you need in a room to get a 50-50 chance that two people have the same birthday? Does anybody

00:03:46.820 --> 00:03:57.580
in the audience know? 33. 23, okay. 23 is the right answer, of course. Never let anybody

00:03:57.779 --> 00:04:04.699
say that it's something else. Python is the developer language. It's for the white space

00:04:04.699 --> 00:04:10.580
enthusiasts that make sure that their indentation is always correct. It's for Zen lovers that

00:04:10.580 --> 00:04:16.820
when they type import this, they get a whole Zen poem. And it can be used for anything,

00:04:16.820 --> 00:04:23.739
not just data science. So already from the start, there's different opinions. But let's

00:04:23.739 --> 00:04:31.299
do some investigations. Who can deliver the quickest? Because there was quite an immediate

00:04:31.299 --> 00:04:37.660
concern, there had been some glitches in the system where the Justice Department needed

00:04:37.660 --> 00:04:44.500
a solution quickly. And overhauling the operational system would take a couple of months. So there

00:04:44.500 --> 00:04:49.459
was a lot of process around making changes to that system. So it was not something that

00:04:49.459 --> 00:04:55.019
they could quickly fix. And so that's where the requirement came for a flexible monitoring

00:04:55.019 --> 00:05:02.980
tool to have a look at anomaly detection. Also inspecting file contents and many more

00:05:02.980 --> 00:05:10.179
things. And that solution needed to be there fast. And Python was actually the quickest

00:05:10.179 --> 00:05:15.420
out of the gate. So most of the stakeholders were already on board with Python. We had

00:05:15.420 --> 00:05:21.660
the IT department that already had some data processing solutions in Python. And also some

00:05:21.660 --> 00:05:27.420
of the checks, for example, for the financial files, the payment files, were already available

00:05:27.420 --> 00:05:32.619
as a Python package. So something that the open source community is really good at in

00:05:32.619 --> 00:05:40.100
building already packaged solutions. And so if Python would have been chosen, then at

00:05:40.100 --> 00:05:46.940
least these things would have been developed already quickly. But we made a counter where

00:05:46.940 --> 00:05:54.940
we used Shiny to build a quick UI mockup, a quick UI demo actually for the actual users

00:05:54.940 --> 00:06:00.779
of the system. We started this project in 2020. So there was no Shiny for Python yet.

00:06:00.779 --> 00:06:08.899
So it had good old classic R Shiny. And there was only one requirement by the end users.

00:06:08.899 --> 00:06:13.500
They wanted to see traffic lights if they looked at the monitoring. So we gave them

00:06:13.500 --> 00:06:17.940
traffic lights, so a dashboard where they could see in the color if things are running

00:06:17.940 --> 00:06:24.260
smoothly, if there are any issues. And they were able to drill down into what is happening.

00:06:24.260 --> 00:06:32.859
So the back office was already on board. And also for the case of R, there were some auditors,

00:06:32.859 --> 00:06:39.619
one of the big four companies actually, that already had some scripts in R that they used

00:06:39.619 --> 00:06:47.779
to do part of their checks and controls. So at this point, it was still balanced.

00:06:47.779 --> 00:06:54.980
But then the question was there, who will be a best fit for production? Because of course,

00:06:54.980 --> 00:07:01.619
the system had to run in production. And if people hear production, Python can have a

00:07:01.619 --> 00:07:11.260
slight edge. So it was already approved by the IT department as a valid use for production.

00:07:11.260 --> 00:07:16.540
And they also had already developers in-house at the Belgian Justice Department who then

00:07:16.540 --> 00:07:23.859
could manage that system. But if you looked at the existing systems, so that was among

00:07:23.859 --> 00:07:29.859
others a data processing system, they did not extend easily for this monitoring case.

00:07:29.859 --> 00:07:34.179
So the things that were needed for the monitoring could not be provided by the system as it

00:07:34.179 --> 00:07:44.019
was running in Python already. So that would have to change. Plus, also, if new use cases

00:07:44.019 --> 00:07:48.899
came up, there were doubts if that system could be extended to tackle all of those use

00:07:48.899 --> 00:07:54.299
cases. But yeah, we still had Python as the only

00:07:54.299 --> 00:08:01.179
option for production. Then you had a good look at what they meant

00:08:01.179 --> 00:08:07.459
by production, because there the opinions can also differ. If you ask data scientists,

00:08:07.459 --> 00:08:13.579
and I think Zhou Cheng had a good article about this, they say that production is if

00:08:13.579 --> 00:08:21.420
you have real users using your app, where there are real consequences if things go wrong,

00:08:21.619 --> 00:08:30.299
it's using real data. That's production. IT has a different view. IT has a view of, well,

00:08:30.299 --> 00:08:35.979
if it's production, then there can be no users logging into the system. There can be no access

00:08:35.979 --> 00:08:42.280
to any terminal executing any commands. That's not allowed. And you shall not install things

00:08:42.280 --> 00:08:48.619
on the fly. You shall not pass. IT had this really strict requirement of keeping something

00:08:48.619 --> 00:08:53.780
in production where not a lot of things were allowed. I think that's very recognizable

00:08:53.780 --> 00:09:01.940
for a lot of data science cases that struggle. So here we faced it as well. But then we had

00:09:01.940 --> 00:09:07.859
a good look at the side of production that we really needed, just real users with real

00:09:07.859 --> 00:09:14.700
consequences and real data. And for that, we didn't need to be in the production environment

00:09:14.700 --> 00:09:24.859
as IT saw it. And then we proposed a platform strategy for production where we looked at

00:09:24.859 --> 00:09:31.460
systems that provided enterprise-level support so that not all of the load was on the IT

00:09:31.460 --> 00:09:37.380
department of actually keeping everything running. There's a proven platform that is

00:09:37.539 --> 00:09:45.099
PositConnect. And by introducing that platform, we also could level the question again, R

00:09:45.099 --> 00:09:54.059
versus Python, as both could be run on this platform. And specifically here, the platform

00:09:54.059 --> 00:10:00.580
would not have to be deployed on what IT considered the production environment. It could be in

00:10:00.580 --> 00:10:05.700
a test environment because from that test environment, there was access to the production

00:10:05.700 --> 00:10:11.460
data. And that was actually all that we needed. Users could access that test environment.

00:10:11.460 --> 00:10:18.780
So we had real users. It was the actual monitoring with actual consequences and using actual

00:10:18.780 --> 00:10:24.859
data. So we did have IT that was not bothered too much if it went down. But as this is not

00:10:24.859 --> 00:10:29.340
the operational system actually processing the fines, that was also not that big of a

00:10:29.340 --> 00:10:37.820
concern. And so we did have the most important thing, real users and real data. And the advantage

00:10:37.820 --> 00:10:44.900
of then choosing this platform strategy is that if we set it up once, all future use

00:10:44.900 --> 00:10:50.099
cases deploying new things to it could then happen often without each time having the

00:10:50.099 --> 00:10:57.299
discussions again with the IT department. And at this point, we are back at an even

00:10:57.299 --> 00:11:06.900
battlefield of R versus Python. If it's even, then we can have a look at if any mediation

00:11:06.900 --> 00:11:15.460
is possible. Can't we all just get along? Combining R and Python in the same deliverable,

00:11:15.460 --> 00:11:21.900
that could be a strategy. So there are packages that follow this strategy. We have great packages

00:11:21.900 --> 00:11:30.140
like Reticulate, R2Py, where you can in the same thing that you're making, combine the

00:11:30.140 --> 00:11:37.260
languages. And in things like Quarto notebooks or in just your R scripts, this is actually

00:11:37.260 --> 00:11:43.419
a very valid strategy where you can use different cells that have different languages and then

00:11:43.419 --> 00:11:50.700
use the objects created in one and the other in a very flexible way. Quarto, if you're

00:11:50.700 --> 00:11:56.979
not using it, you should be. It's really a powerful framework to deliver all kinds

00:11:56.979 --> 00:12:05.039
of things. For example, presentations on PositConf as well. But it was more tricky to combine

00:12:05.039 --> 00:12:13.580
R and Python in the same code for building a shiny API thing. And so then combining it

00:12:13.580 --> 00:12:19.219
in the same deliverable was not the best approach. And so it was also not seen as the solution

00:12:19.260 --> 00:12:29.700
in this case here. And then we took a step back at how do other software systems solve

00:12:29.700 --> 00:12:37.340
this? And you actually have a lot of patterns, frameworks, approaches, methodologies that

00:12:37.340 --> 00:12:42.219
are general for software development. But for data science, sometimes it feels like

00:12:42.299 --> 00:12:49.580
new strategies. But just splitting your software into different components, modules, sometimes

00:12:49.580 --> 00:12:56.900
Microsoft services, if you're Netflix or somebody like that. But just splitting your architecture

00:12:56.900 --> 00:13:02.979
in multiple components, that's actually also a way that you combine multiple programming

00:13:02.979 --> 00:13:12.099
frameworks in a good way. And I think Posit also has very good documentation on this.

00:13:12.099 --> 00:13:16.580
There's on their website the bike prediction case, where you have a more elaborate architecture

00:13:16.580 --> 00:13:25.460
that has ETL steps, where there's Quarto documents or Markdown documents that connect to some

00:13:25.460 --> 00:13:30.739
source data, perform some transformations, and publish clean data sets with the Pins

00:13:30.739 --> 00:13:37.859
package, who then also run a Quarto document to train a machine learning model on that

00:13:37.859 --> 00:13:44.619
Pins data set, also publish that model in a Plumber API, and then using that API in

00:13:44.619 --> 00:13:50.059
a Shiny application. And so with something like Connect, you can actually build these

00:13:50.059 --> 00:13:57.140
more elaborate architectures, but just on the same platform. And then dividing your

00:13:57.140 --> 00:14:03.140
use case into multiple little pieces that are easier to manage, easier to maintain,

00:14:03.140 --> 00:14:10.619
easier to make changes, easier also to evolve and get new people on board and contributing

00:14:10.619 --> 00:14:17.500
to your architecture. And I think it's a very well-documented solution, where you have the

00:14:17.500 --> 00:14:23.900
source codes, all the steps that they do. So definitely something to check out.

00:14:23.900 --> 00:14:29.780
And it's also the strategy that we ultimately chose for the cross-border monitoring architecture.

00:14:29.780 --> 00:14:36.340
So the monitoring of the traffic finds, where on PositConnect, we could use our Shiny as

00:14:36.340 --> 00:14:43.419
our monitoring dashboard, which then connects to a monitoring API that was built in Python,

00:14:43.419 --> 00:14:49.820
that uses the results of ETL that is also running in Python. And actually for the checks,

00:14:49.820 --> 00:14:57.179
it made sense to have some checks written in Python, some checks written in R, and then

00:14:57.179 --> 00:15:05.900
combine all of these things into a very efficient and performant monitoring architecture.

00:15:05.900 --> 00:15:11.460
So this way we can reach a verdict. And I think as you all expected, probably, it wasn't

00:15:11.460 --> 00:15:19.179
the story about R or Python. It's actually the story of R and Python, where using them

00:15:19.179 --> 00:15:25.940
together, we could make real speed in making innovation and efficiency possible for the

00:15:25.940 --> 00:15:32.219
Belgian Justice Department. I think there's a lot of things that data science here can

00:15:32.219 --> 00:15:39.619
learn from the classical software architecture and how to approach these kinds of architectures.

00:15:39.619 --> 00:15:46.700
And also for me, the data science can have more broad applications than just the top

00:15:46.700 --> 00:15:51.219
high-end machine learning cases. I think in a business context, there's a lot of things

00:15:51.219 --> 00:15:56.419
that where data plays an important role, where the focus is more on the analysis rather

00:15:56.419 --> 00:16:01.700
than the process. So I don't think we'll ever see a traffic fine processing system

00:16:01.700 --> 00:16:07.900
built in R or Python. But there's a lot of things around it that can be more data-driven.

00:16:07.900 --> 00:16:12.700
And I think this monitoring case is a very relevant one, where you have anomaly detection,

00:16:12.700 --> 00:16:17.419
where there are some algorithms that can help, but just the full end-to-end architecture

00:16:17.419 --> 00:16:23.059
where you have real users using an application that gets warnings and alerts, and they can

00:16:23.059 --> 00:16:31.059
have a very small workflow. It's a very good case for data science and R and Python.

00:16:31.059 --> 00:16:35.580
And I think in this case, the verdict was reached by the Belgian justice system. So

00:16:35.580 --> 00:16:42.739
from now on, no more discussions of R or Python, but it's a question of R and Python.

00:16:42.739 --> 00:16:44.739
Thank you very much for your attention.

00:16:44.739 --> 00:16:54.739
Thank you so much. We have a few questions for you. The first one is, did Reticulate

00:16:54.739 --> 00:17:00.380
give you any headache when deploying apps that use both R and Python code?

00:17:00.380 --> 00:17:06.739
Not in this case, but in a lot of cases, it has indeed. It can be a bit tricky to set

00:17:06.739 --> 00:17:13.380
it up correctly. And I think if you have cases where you can use some R code and Python

00:17:13.380 --> 00:17:18.300
code that don't have to exchange too many objects, then it can work perfectly. If it

00:17:18.300 --> 00:17:23.900
comes tightly interwoven, it can give headaches. Yes, that's true.

00:17:23.900 --> 00:17:30.020
One more question. Do you have a view on Plumber for APIs in R versus the abundance of Python

00:17:30.020 --> 00:17:33.819
API libraries, like Flask or FastAPI?

00:17:34.540 --> 00:17:43.459
In this case, we actually chose Flask as the API. And in a lot of cases, I think Python

00:17:43.459 --> 00:17:50.300
does have an edge. And I think the FastAPI, for example, is a very, very powerful API

00:17:50.300 --> 00:17:58.819
framework. I think Plumber has the advantage of it's easy for R users to also get started.

00:17:58.819 --> 00:18:04.459
And there is also, if there's a lot of R stuff happening in your API, then Plumber

00:18:04.459 --> 00:18:08.140
makes more sense. So, for example, if you would have R markdown documents that you need

00:18:08.140 --> 00:18:15.420
to generate, it makes more sense to keep it in the R framework, use Plumber to generate

00:18:15.420 --> 00:18:21.380
that document. And I think the cases where we used it, there is some consideration in

00:18:21.380 --> 00:18:28.500
terms of how to scale it. But then if you have something like the RStudio or deposit

00:18:28.500 --> 00:18:35.140
connect platform, there's ways to control how many users target the same Plumber API

00:18:35.140 --> 00:18:42.300
at the same time. And if you use it, for example, like in a cloud context on Azure, for example,

00:18:42.300 --> 00:18:47.060
you have Azure container apps where you can also scale your Plumber app. So, that downside

00:18:47.060 --> 00:18:51.180
doesn't have to be really a downside. So, I think for me, it's more about what does

00:18:51.180 --> 00:18:56.660
the API do and is there something specific with R than use Plumber? And otherwise, I

00:18:56.660 --> 00:18:59.859
think Python does have an edge with FastAPI. Yes.

00:18:59.859 --> 00:19:02.819
Thank you so much. We can give one more round of applause.

